, Guy. 2013. \"[http://www.gramophone.co.uk/review/ch\u00e1vez-symphonies-nos-1-6?pmtx=orange-all Ch\u00e1vez Symphonies 1\u20136]\". ''Gramophone'' (9 January).}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archives.nyphil.org/index.php/artifact/e20bd423-02c5-4d34-9f1b-cd3460c96045?search-type=singleFilter&search-text=Chavez&doctype=printedMusic&x=24&y=6&search-dates-from=&search-dates-to= Leonard Bernstein's marked conducting score of Carlos Ch\u00e1vez, Symphony No. 6]. Leon Levy Digital Collection: International Era 1943\u20131970. New York Philharmonic Digital Archive (Accessed 3 July 2012).\n\n{{Ch\u00e1vez symphonies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Symphony No. 6 (Chavez)}}\n[[Category:Symphonies by Carlos Ch\u00e1vez| 06]]\n[[Category:20th-century symphonies|Ch\u00e1vez  6]]\n[[Category:1962 compositions]]\n[[Category:Music commissioned by the New York Philharmonic]]\n[[Category:Music dedicated to ensembles or performers]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symphony_No._6_(Ch%C3%A1vez)"}
{"title_page": "Scott Mactavish", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n'''Scott Mactavish''' is an American [[filmmaker]] and author.\n\nScott Mactavish recently wrote, produced and directed the films entitled ''MURPH: The Protector'' and ''God and Country: Untold Stories of the American Military''.<ref name=whsv>{{cite web|title=Local Military Documentary|url=http://www.whsv.com/home/headlines/13064497.html?storySection=story|work=[[WHSV-TV|WHSV.com]]|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=armyTimes4Jan2008>{{cite web|last=McKenzie|first=Bryan|title=Filmmaker Marine fights Hollywood stereotype|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2008/01/ap_filmmaker_080104/|work=[[Army Times]]|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref>   Prior to that, he made ''Summer Running: The Race to Cure Breast Cancer'' featuring [[Sissy Spacek]]. He has also served as executive producer on five films in as many years, including ''Chagas'', directed by [[Ricardo Preve]]. Mactavish attended film School at [[New York University]], and upon graduation, worked on major studio projects and independent features while writing original screenplays at night.  He was a [[Goomba]] in the 1993 film [[Super Mario Bros. (film)|''Super Mario Bros.'']] and an uncredited stunt double in ''[[The Crow (1994 film)|The Crow]]''. He launched his own production company in 1998 and has produced dozens of films and videos, with an emphasis on stories of honor, courage and commitment.\n\nScott is the author of ''The New Dad's Survival Guide'', published by [[Little, Brown and Co.]], and co-author of ''Battle Ready: Memoir of a SEAL Warrior Medic'', published by [[St. Martin's Press]].\n\nAs a freelance writer, he has contributed to ''[[Indiewire]]'', ''[[Windcheck]]'', and ''[[Film Threat]]''.\n\nMactavish is a veteran of the [[United States Navy]].  He attended boot camp at the Recruit Training Command in [[San Diego, California]] and served with Submarine Squadron 6, aboard the USS L.Y. Spear, and in [[Guantanamo Bay, Cuba]].<ref>[http://www.scottmactavish.com/?page_id=201 ''Official Biography'']. Scott Mactavish Biography</ref><ref>[http://www.virginia.edu/symrs/speaker_mactavish.html \"University of Virginia Speaker Bio\"]. Guest Speaker Biography</ref>\n\n== Movies ==\n*''Family Mission: The TJ Lobraico Story'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''MURPH: The Protector'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''Ride for Lance'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''God and Country: Untold Stories of the American Military'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''Summer Running: The Race to Cure Breast Cancer'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''Chagas:  A Hidden Affliction'' - Executive Producer\n*''Stickball Boulevard'' - Executive Producer\n\n==Books==\n*''The New Dad's Survival Guide''\n*''Battle Ready: Memoir of a SEAL Warrior Medic''\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mactavish.us Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|0534372}}\n*[http://www.murphmovie.com MURPH: The Protector]\n*[http://www.dadbook.com The New Dad's Survival Guide]\n*[http://www.rideforlance.com Ride for Lance]\n*[http://www.murphmovie.com MURPH: The Protector]\n*[http://us.macmillan.com/battleready/MarkDonald Battle Ready: Memoir of a SEAL Warrior Medic]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mactavish, Scott}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:American filmmakers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n'''Scott Mactavish''' is an American [[filmmaker]] and author.\n\nScott Mactavish recently wrote, produced and directed the films entitled ''MURPH: The Protector'' and ''God and Country: Untold Stories of the American Military''.<ref name=whsv>{{cite web|title=Local Military Documentary|url=http://www.whsv.com/home/headlines/13064497.html?storySection=story|work=[[WHSV-TV|WHSV.com]]|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=armyTimes4Jan2008>{{cite web|last=McKenzie|first=Bryan|title=Filmmaker Marine fights Hollywood stereotype|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2008/01/ap_filmmaker_080104/|work=[[Army Times]]|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref>   Prior to that, he made ''Summer Running: The Race to Cure Breast Cancer'' featuring [[Sissy Spacek]]. He has also served as executive producer on five films in as many years, including ''Chagas'', directed by [[Ricardo Preve]]. Mactavish attended film School at [[New York University]], and upon graduation, worked on major studio projects and independent features while writing original screenplays at night.  He was a [[Goomba]] in the 1993 film [[Super Mario Bros. (film)|''Super Mario Bros.'']] and an uncredited stunt double in ''[[The Crow (1994 film)|The Crow]]''. He launched his own production company in 1998 and has produced dozens of films and videos, with an emphasis on stories of honor, courage and commitment.\n\nScott is the author of ''The New Dad's Survival Guide'', published by [[Little, Brown and Co.]], and co-author of ''Battle Ready: Memoir of a SEAL Warrior Medic'', published by [[St. Martin's Press]].\n\nAs a freelance writer, he has contributed to ''[[Indiewire]]'', ''[[Windcheck]]'', and ''[[Film Threat]]''.\n\nMactavish is a veteran of the [[United States Navy]].  He attended boot camp at the Recruit Training Command in [[San Diego, California]] and served with Submarine Squadron 6, aboard the USS L.Y. Spear, and in [[Guantanamo Bay, Cuba]].<ref>[http://www.scottmactavish.com/?page_id=201 ''Official Biography'']. Scott Mactavish Biography</ref><ref>[http://www.virginia.edu/symrs/speaker_mactavish.html \"University of Virginia Speaker Bio\"]. Guest Speaker Biography</ref>\n\n== Movies ==\n*''Family Mission: The TJ Lobraico Story'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''MURPH: The Protector'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''Ride for Lance'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''God and Country: Untold Stories of the American Military'' - Writer, Producer, Director\n*''Summer